            <group xml:id="en_Prolusioni" xml:lang="EN" > <!--TRADUZIONI INGLESE DELLE 3 PROLUSIONI-->
                <text xml:id="en_Prolusione-1"> <!--EN 1 PROLUSIONE-->
                    <body resp="#AC" xml:id="body-inglese" source="#WGL">
                        <div xml:id="div_p8_en" hand="#h1" type="box_testo_en">
                            <ab xml:id="en_91Aaaa017" corresp="#pericope_91Aaaa017" xml:lang="EN">
                                <lb/>This is were the following objection, 
                                <lb/>more or les well founded in my view, occurs: you are transforming the study 
                                <lb/>of languages into the study of langage,
                                <lb/>of langage taken as a human faculty, as one of the distinguishing features
                                <lb/>of the species, as an anthropological,
                                <lb/>or soto speak, zoological characteristic.     
                            </ab> 
                            <ab xml:id="en_91Aaaa018" corresp="#pericope_91Aaaa018" xml:lang="EN">
                                <lb/>Gentlemen, 
                                <lb/>I should need some considerable time 
                                <lb/>to set out, develop, and justify my view touching this point, 
                                <lb/>which is no different from that 
                                <lb/>of all linguists today: it is that 
                                <lb/>it is entirely or almost entirely, within the study of languages 
                                <lb/>that one studies language as a human phenomenon.
                            </ab>                             
                            <ab xml:id="en_91Aaaa019" corresp="#pericope_91Aaaa019" xml:lang="EN">
                                <lb/>Physiologists, psychologists, and logicians may hold forth 
                                <lb/>at length, philosophers may then take up the combined results 
                                <lb/>of logic, psychology, and 
                                <lb/>physiology; nut I male so bold as to say that the most elementary 
                                <lb/>phenomena of language will never be glimpsed, 
                                <lb/>let alone clearly perceived, classified, and understood, unless we 
                                <lb/>take as our starting point and our goal the study of individual 
                                <lb/>languages.
                            </ab>                     
                            <ab xml:id="en_91Aaaa020" corresp="#pericope_91Aaaa020" xml:lang="EN">
                                <lb/>The language system (langue) and the language faculty (langage) come back to one 
                                <lb/>and the same thing; one is the generalization 
                                <lb/>of the other         
                            </ab>                            
                            <ab xml:id="en_91Aaaa021" corresp="#pericope_91Aaaa021" xml:lang="EN">
                                <lb/>To claim to study the phenomenon of language (...)
                            </ab>

                        </div>                         
                    </body>
                </text>       
